	"\e[0mYou teach best what you most need to learn.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mRichard Bach\e[0m"
	"\e[0mContinuous effort, not strength or intelligence is the key to unlocking our potential.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mWinston Churchill\e[0m"
	"\e[0mObstacles are those frightful things you see when you take your eyes off your goal.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mHenry Ford\e[0m"
	"\e[0mGo for it now. The future is promised to no one.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mWayne Dyer\e[0m"
	"\e[0mNever tell a young person that anything cannot be done. God may have been waiting centuries for someone ignorant enough of the impossible to do that very thing.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mJohn Holmes\e[0m"
	"\e[0mBold is not the act of foolishness but the attribute and inner strength to act when others will not so as to move forward not backward.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mByron Pulsifer\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf we look at the world with a love of life, the world will reveal its beauty to us.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mDaisaku Ikeda\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIn skating over thin ice our safety is in our speed.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mRalph Emerson\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWhen you discover your mission, you will feel its demand. It will fill you with enthusiasm and a burning desire to get to work on it.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mW. Clement Stone\e[0m"
	"\e[0mNever promise more than you can perform.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mPublilius Syrus\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf you don't go after what you want, you'll never have it. If you don't ask, the answer is always no. If you don't step forward, you're always in the same place.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mNora Roberts\e[0m"
	"\e[0mI can't believe that God put us on this earth to be ordinary.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mLou Holtz\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThere are no limitations to the mind except those we acknowledge.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mNapoleon Hill\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIt is through science that we prove, but through intuition that we discover.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mJules Poincare\e[0m"
	"\e[0mDon't be dismayed by good-byes. A farewell is necessary before you can meet again. And meeting again, after moments or lifetimes, is certain for those who are friends.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mRichard Bach\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf someone in your life talked to you the way you talk to yourself, you would have left them long ago.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mCarla Gordon\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe cosmos is neither moral or immoral; only people are. He who would move the world must first move himself.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mEdward Ericson\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf you lose today, win tomorrow. In this never-ending spirit of challenge is the heart of a victor.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mDaisaku Ikeda\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThere is a way that nature speaks, that land speaks. Most of the time we are simply not patient enough, quiet enough, to pay attention to the story.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mLinda Hogan\e[0m"
	"\e[0mNever tell me the sky is the limit when there are footprints on the moon.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mnull\e[0m"
	"\e[0mI cannot say whether things will get better if we change; what I can say is they must change if they are to get better.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mGeorg Lichtenberg\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe greater part of human pain is unnecessary. It is self-created as long as the unobserved mind runs your life.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mEckhart Tolle\e[0m"
	"\e[0mTake it easy but take it.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mWoody Guthrie\e[0m"
	"\e[0mBlessed is the man who expects nothing, for he shall never be disappointed.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlexander Pope\e[0m"
	"\e[0mHe who knows others is wise. He who knows himself is enlightened.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mLao Tzu\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe best way to predict your future is to create it.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mPeter Drucker\e[0m"
	"\e[0mA garden is always a series of losses set against a few triumphs, like life itself.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mMay Sarton\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf facts are the seeds that later produce knowledge and wisdom, then the emotions and the impressions of the senses are the fertile soil in which the seeds must grow.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mRachel Carson\e[0m"
	"\e[0mNever mistake motion for action.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mErnest Hemingway\e[0m"
	"\e[0mOne needs something to believe in, something for which one can have whole-hearted enthusiasm. One needs to feel that ones life has meaning, that one is needed in this world.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mHannah Senesh\e[0m"
	"\e[0mOne who is too insistent on his own views, finds few to agree with him.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mLao Tzu\e[0m"
	"\e[0mTranslation is the paradigm, the exemplar of all writing. It is translation that demonstrates most vividly the yearning for transformation that underlies every act involving speech, that supremely human gift.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mHarry Burchell Mathews\e[0m"
	"\e[0mMeditation is the dissolution of thoughts in eternal awareness or Pure consciousness without objectification, knowing without thinking, merging finitude in infinity.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mVoltaire\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe reasonable man adapts himself to the world; the unreasonable man persists in trying to adapt the world to himself. Therefore, all progress depends on the unreasonable man.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mGeorge Shaw\e[0m"
	"\e[0mGood instincts usually tell you what to do long before your head has figured it out.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mMichael Burke\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIt isn't what happens to us that causes us to suffer; it's what we say to ourselves about what happens.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mPema Chodron\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThose who dream by day are cognizant of many things which escape those who dream only by night.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mEdgar Allan Poe\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWe cannot hold a torch to light another's path without brightening our own.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mBen Sweetland\e[0m"
	"\e[0mYou are never given a wish without also being given the power to make it come true. You may have to work for it, however.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mRichard Bach\e[0m"
	"\e[0mKind words can be short and easy to speak, but their echoes are truly endless.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mMother Teresa\e[0m"
	"\e[0mCount your joys instead of your woes. Count your friends instead of your foes.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mnull\e[0m"
	"\e[0mDreams come true. Without that possibility, nature would not incite us to have them.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mJohn Updike\e[0m"
	"\e[0mStaying in one place is the best path to be taken over and surpassed by many.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mByron Pulsifer\e[0m"
	"\e[0mImagination will often carry us to worlds that never were. But without it we go nowhere.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mCarl Sagan\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWhen one door of happiness closes, another opens; but often we look so long at the closed door that we do not see the one which has been opened for us.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mHelen Keller\e[0m"
	"\e[0mA leader or a man of action in a crisis almost always acts subconsciously and then thinks of the reasons for his action.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mJawaharlal Nehru\e[0m"
	"\e[0mI have no special talent. I am only passionately curious.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlbert Einstein\e[0m"
	"\e[0mI endeavour to be wise when I cannot be merry, easy when I cannot be glad, content with what cannot be mended and patient when there is no redress.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mElizabeth Montagu\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe height of your accomplishments will equal the depth of your convictions.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mWilliam Scolavino\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf I am not for myself, who will be for me? If I am not for others, what am I? And if not now, when?\n\t\e[1m\e[96mRabbi Hillel\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWhen I dare to be powerful, to use my strength in the service of my vision, then it becomes less and less important whether I am afraid.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAudre Lorde\e[0m"
	"\e[0mAll great men are gifted with intuition. They know without reasoning or analysis, what they need to know.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlexis Carrel\e[0m"
	"\e[0mTo get the full value of joy you must have someone to divide it with.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mMark Twain\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSometimes our fate resembles a fruit tree in winter. Who would think that those branches would turn green again and blossom, but we hope it, we know it.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mJohann Wolfgang von Goethe\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWe lost because we told ourselves we lost.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mLeo Tolstoy\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSuccess is determined by those whom prove the impossible, possible.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mJames Pence\e[0m"
	"\e[0mGood advice is always certain to be ignored, but that's no reason not to give it.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAgatha Christie\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe winner ain't the one with the fastest car it's the one who refuses to lose.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mDale Earnhardt\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSpirituality can be severed from both vicious sectarianism and thoughtless banalities. Spirituality, I have come to see, is nothing less than the thoughtful love of life.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mRobert C. Solomon\e[0m"
	"\e[0mNo one has a finer command of language than the person who keeps his mouth shut.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mSam Rayburn\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe only person who never makes mistakes is the person who never does anything.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mDenis Waitley\e[0m"
	"\e[0mLife is what happens to you while you're busy making other plans.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mJohn Lennon\e[0m"
	"\e[0mDiscovery consists of seeing what everybody has seen and thinking what nobody else has thought.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mJonathan Swift\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf you have knowledge, let others light their candles in it.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mMargaret Fuller\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIt is impossible for a man to learn what he thinks he already knows.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mEpictetus\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf you find yourself in a hole, the first thing to do is stop digging.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mWill Rogers\e[0m"
	"\e[0mTo make no mistakes is not in the power of man; but from their errors and mistakes the wise and good learn wisdom for the future.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mPlutarch\e[0m"
	"\e[0mI think you can have moderate success by copying something else, but if you really want to knock it out of the park, you have to do something different and take chances.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mLee Womack\e[0m"
	"\e[0mEverything we hear is an opinion, not a fact. Everything we see is a perspective, not the truth.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mMarcus Aurelius\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSix essential qualities that are the key to success: Sincerity, personal integrity, humility, courtesy, wisdom, charity.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mWilliam Menninger\e[0m"
	"\e[0mI have an everyday religion that works for me. Love yourself first, and everything else falls into line.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mLucille Ball\e[0m"
	"\e[0mFlow with whatever is happening and let your mind be free. Stay centred by accepting whatever you are doing. This is the ultimate.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mChuang Tzu\e[0m"
	"\e[0mNothing could be worse than the fear that one had given up too soon, and left one unexpended effort that might have saved the world.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mJane Addams\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe energy of the mind is the essence of life.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAristotle\e[0m"
	"\e[0mBegin, be bold, and venture to be wise.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mHorace\e[0m"
	"\e[0mGive a man a fish and you feed him for a day. Teach him how to fish and you feed him for a lifetime.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mLao Tzu\e[0m"
	"\e[0mA wise man will make more opportunities than he finds.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mFrancis Bacon\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSlow down and enjoy life. It's not only the scenery you miss by going too fast you also miss the sense of where you are going and why.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mEddie Cantor\e[0m"
	"\e[0mMiracles come in moments. Be ready and willing.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mWayne Dyer\e[0m"
	"\e[0mNumberless are the worlds wonders, but none more wonderful than man.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mSophocles\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSo is cheerfulness, or a good temper, the more it is spent, the more remains.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mRalph Emerson\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe true way to render ourselves happy is to love our work and find in it our pleasure.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mFrancoise de Motteville\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWhen you judge another, you do not define them, you define yourself.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mWayne Dyer\e[0m"
	"\e[0mArgue for your limitations, and sure enough they're yours.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mRichard Bach\e[0m"
	"\e[0mHe who wishes to secure the good of others, has already secured his own.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mConfucius\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWise men talk because they have something to say; fools, because they have to say something.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mPlato\e[0m"
	"\e[0mLife is really simple, but we insist on making it complicated.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mConfucius\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe future is an opaque mirror. Anyone who tries to look into it sees nothing but the dim outlines of an old and worried face.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mJim Bishop\e[0m"
	"\e[0mEverything that irritates us about others can lead us to a better understanding of ourselves.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mCarl Jung\e[0m"
	"\e[0mBeware of the half truth. You may have gotten hold of the wrong half.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mnull\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe greatest mistake you can make in life is to be continually fearing you will make one.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mElbert Hubbard\e[0m"
	"\e[0mI have never been hurt by anything I didn't say.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mCalvin Coolidge\e[0m"
	"\e[0mBe not angry that you cannot make others as you wish them to be, since you cannot make yourself as you wish to be.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mThomas Kempis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mAdversity causes some men to break, others to break records.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mWilliam Ward\e[0m"
	"\e[0mAn invincible determination can accomplish almost anything and in this lies the great distinction between great men and little men.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mThomas Fuller\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe industrial landscape is already littered with remains of once successful companies that could not adapt their strategic vision to altered conditions of competition.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAbernathy\e[0m"
	"\e[0mExample has more followers than reason.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mChristian Bovee\e[0m"
	"\e[0mOne that desires to excel should endeavour in those things that are in themselves most excellent.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mEpictetus\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf you have made mistakes, there is always another chance for you. You may have a fresh start any moment you choose.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mMary Pickford\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe only Zen you find on the tops of mountains is the Zen you bring up there.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mRobert Pirsig\e[0m"
	"\e[0mGratitude is riches. Complaint is poverty.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mDoris Day\e[0m"
	"\e[0mStrong people make as many mistakes as weak people. Difference is that strong people admit their mistakes, laugh at them, learn from them. That is how they become strong.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mRichard Needham\e[0m"
	"\e[0mTo know your purpose is to live a life of direction, and in that direction is found peace and tranquillity.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mByron Pulsifer\e[0m"
	"\e[0mYou can stand tall without standing on someone. You can be a victor without having victims.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mHarriet Woods\e[0m"
	"\e[0mBad times have a scientific value. These are occasions a good learner would not miss.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mRalph Emerson\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIt's not who you are that holds you back, it's who you think you're not.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mnull\e[0m"
	"\e[0mAll children are artists. The problem is how to remain an artist once he grows up.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mPablo Picasso\e[0m"
	"\e[0mEither I will find a way, or I will make one.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mPhilip Sidney\e[0m"
	"\e[0mHe who knows that enough is enough will always have enough.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mLao Tzu\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe only way to have a friend is to be one.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mRalph Emerson\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf we had no winter, the spring would not be so pleasant; if we did not sometimes taste of adversity, prosperity would not be so welcome.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAnne Bradstreet\e[0m"
	"\e[0mJoy is what happens to us when we allow ourselves to recognize how good things really are.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mMarianne Williamson\e[0m"
	"\e[0mYour vision will become clear only when you can look into your own heart. Who looks outside, dreams; who looks inside, awakes.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mCarl Jung\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThere is never enough time to do everything, but there is always enough time to do the most important thing.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mBrian Tracy\e[0m"
	"\e[0mYou really can change the world if you care enough.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mMarian Edelman\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWhat you are is what you have been. What you will be is what you do now.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mBuddha\e[0m"
	"\e[0mOur lives are the only meaningful expression of what we believe and in Whom we believe. And the only real wealth, for any of us, lies in our faith.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mGordon Hinckley\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThere surely is in human nature an inherent propensity to extract all the good out of all the evil.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mBenjamin Haydon\e[0m"
	"\e[0mMusic in the soul can be heard by the universe.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mLao Tzu\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWhat we see depends mainly on what we look for.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mJohn Lubbock\e[0m"
	"\e[0mTo hell with circumstances; I create opportunities.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mBruce Lee\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe truest greatness lies in being kind, the truest wisdom in a happy mind.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mElla Wilcox\e[0m"
	"\e[0mAn ounce of emotion is equal to a ton of facts.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mJohn Junor\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWe need to find the courage to say NO to the things and people that are not serving us if we want to rediscover ourselves and live our lives with authenticity.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mBarbara De Angelis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mGreat is the art of beginning, but greater is the art of ending.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mLazurus Long\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSimply put, you believer that things or people make you unhappy, but this is not accurate. You make yourself unhappy.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mWayne Dyer\e[0m"
	"\e[0mNothing will work unless you do.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mMaya Angelou\e[0m"
	"\e[0mOur ability to achieve happiness and success depends on the strength of our wings.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mCatherine Pulsifer\e[0m"
	"\e[0mTo go against the dominant thinking of your friends, of most of the people you see every day, is perhaps the most difficult act of heroism you can perform.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mTheodore H. White\e[0m"
	"\e[0mGratitude makes sense of our past, brings peace for today, and creates a vision for tomorrow.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mMelody Beattie\e[0m"
	"\e[0mInto each life rain must fall but rain can be the giver of life and it is all in your attitude that makes rain produce sunshine.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mByron Pulsifer\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWe are all inclined to judge ourselves by our ideals; others, by their acts.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mHarold Nicolson\e[0m"
	"\e[0mNothing is a waste of time if you use the experience wisely.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mRodin\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf one way be better than another, that you may be sure is natures way.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAristotle\e[0m"
	"\e[0mHere is one quality that one must possess to win, and that is definiteness of purpose, the knowledge of what one wants, and a burning desire to possess it.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mNapoleon Hill\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIt is not in the stars to hold our destiny but in ourselves.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mWilliam Shakespeare\e[0m"
	"\e[0mUsing the power of decision gives you the capacity to get past any excuse to change any and every part of your life in an instant.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mTony Robbins\e[0m"
	"\e[0mI will prepare and some day my chance will come.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAbraham Lincoln\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSometimes the cards we are dealt are not always fair. However you must keep smiling and moving on.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mTom Jackson\e[0m"
	"\e[0mTalk is cheap. Show me the code.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mLinus Torvalds\e[0m"
	"\e[0mMost good programmers do programming not because they expect to get paid or get adulation by the public, but because it is fun to program.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mLinus Torvalds\e[0m"
	"\e[0mI'm an egotistical bastard, and I name all my projects after myself. First Linux, now git.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mLinus Torvalds\e[0m"
	"\e[0mOne man's constant is another man's variable.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mFunctions delay binding; data structures induce binding. Moral: Structure data late in the programming process.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSyntactic sugar causes cancer of the semicolon.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mEvery program is a part of some other program and rarely fits.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf a program manipulates a large amount of data, it does so in a small number of ways.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSymmetry is a complexity-reducing concept (co-routines include subroutines); seek it everywhere.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIt is easier to write an incorrect program than understand a correct one.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mA programming language is low level when its programs require attention to the irrelevant.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIt is better to have 100 functions operate on one data structure than 10 functions on 10 data structures.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mGet into a rut early: Do the same process the same way. Accumulate idioms. Standardize. The only difference(!) between Shakespeare and you was the size of his idiom list - not the size of his vocabulary.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf you have a procedure with ten parameters, you probably missed some.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mRecursion is the root of computation since it trades description for time.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf two people write exactly the same program, each should be put into microcode and then they certainly won't be the same.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIn the long run every program becomes rococo - then rubble.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mEverything should be built top-down, except the first time.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mEvery program has (at least) two purposes: the one for which it was written, and another for which it wasn't.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf a listener nods his head when you're explaining your program, wake him up.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mA program without a loop and a structured variable isn't worth writing.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mA language that doesn't affect the way you think about programming, is not worth knowing.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWherever there is modularity there is the potential for misunderstanding: Hiding information implies a need to check communication.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mOptimization hinders evolution.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mA good system can't have a weak command language.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mTo understand a program you must become both the machine and the program.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mPerhaps if we wrote programs from childhood on, as adults we'd be able to read them.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mOne can only display complex information in the mind. Like seeing, movement or flow or alteration of view is more important than the static picture, no matter how lovely.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThere will always be things we wish to say in our programs that in all known languages can only be said poorly.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mOnce you understand how to write a program get someone else to write it.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mAround computers it is difficult to find the correct unit of time to measure progress. Some cathedrals took a century to complete. Can you imagine the grandeur and scope of a program that would take as long?\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mFor systems, the analogue of a face-lift is to add to the control graph an edge that creates a cycle, not just an additional node.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIn programming, everything we do is a special case of something more general -- and often we know it too quickly.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSimplicity does not precede complexity, but follows it.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mProgrammers are not to be measured by their ingenuity and their logic but by the completeness of their case analysis.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe eleventh commandment was \"Thou Shalt Compute\" or \"Thou Shalt Not Compute\" - I forget which.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe string is a stark data structure and everywhere it is passed there is much duplication of process. It is a perfect vehicle for hiding information.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mEveryone can be taught to sculpt: Michelangelo would have had to be taught not to. So it is with great programmers.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe use of a program to prove the 4-color theorem will not change mathematics - it merely demonstrates that the theorem, a challenge for a century, is probably not important to mathematics.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe most important computer is the one that rages in our skulls and ever seeks that satisfactory external emulator. The standarization of real computers would be a disaster - and so it probably won't happen.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mStructured Programming supports the law of the excluded middle.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mRe graphics: A picture is worth 10K words - but only those to describe the picture. Hardly any sets of 10K words can be adequately described with pictures.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThere are two ways to write error-free programs; only the third one works.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSome programming languages manage to absorb change, but withstand progress.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mYou can measure a programmer's perspective by noting his attitude on the continuing vitality of FORTRAN.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIn software systems, it is often the early bird that makes the worm.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSometimes I think the only universal in the computing field is the fetch-execute cycle.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe goal of computation is the emulation of our synthetic abilities, not the understanding of our analytic ones.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mLike punning, programming is a play on words.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mAs Will Rogers would have said, \"There is no such thing as a free variable.\"\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe best book on programming for the layman is \"Alice in Wonderland\"; but that's because it's the best book on anything for the layman.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mGiving up on assembly language was the apple in our Garden of Eden: Languages whose use squanders machine cycles are sinful. The LISP machine now permits LISP programmers to abandon bra and fig-leaf.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWhen we understand knowledge-based systems, it will be as before -- except our fingertips will have been singed.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mBringing computers into the home won't change either one, but may revitalize the corner saloon.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSystems have sub-systems and sub-systems have sub-systems and so on ad infinitum - which is why we're always starting over.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSo many good ideas are never heard from again once they embark in a voyage on the semantic gulf.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mBeware of the Turing tar-pit in which everything is possible but nothing of interest is easy.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mA LISP programmer knows the value of everything, but the cost of nothing.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSoftware is under a constant tension. Being symbolic it is arbitrarily perfectible; but also it is arbitrarily changeable.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIt is easier to change the specification to fit the program than vice versa.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mFools ignore complexity. Pragmatists suffer it. Some can avoid it. Geniuses remove it.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIn English every word can be verbed. Would that it were so in our programming languages.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIn seeking the unattainable, simplicity only gets in the way.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIn programming, as in everything else, to be in error is to be reborn.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIn computing, invariants are ephemeral.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWhen we write programs that \"learn\", it turns out that we do and they don't.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mOften it is the means that justify the ends: Goals advance technique and technique survives even when goal structures crumble.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mMake no mistake about it: Computers process numbers - not symbols. We measure our understanding (and control) by the extent to which we can arithmetize an activity.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mMaking something variable is easy. Controlling duration of constancy is the trick.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThink of all the psychic energy expended in seeking a fundamental distinction between \"algorithm\" and \"program\".\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf we believe in data structures, we must believe in independent (hence simultaneous) processing. For why else would we collect items within a structure? Why do we tolerate languages that give us the one without the other?\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIn a 5 year period we get one superb programming language. Only we can't control when the 5 year period will be.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mOver the centuries the Indians developed sign language for communicating phenomena of interest. Programmers from different tribes (FORTRAN, LISP, ALGOL, SNOBOL, etc.) could use one that doesn't require them to carry a blackboard on their ponies.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mDocumentation is like term insurance: It satisfies because almost no one who subscribes to it depends on its benefits.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mAn adequate bootstrap is a contradiction in terms.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIt is not a language's weakness but its strengths that control the gradient of its change: Alas, a language never escapes its embryonic sac.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIs it possible that software is not like anything else, that it is meant to be discarded: that the whole point is to see it as a soap bubble?\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mBecause of its vitality, the computing field is always in desperate need of new cliches: Banality soothes our nerves.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIt is the user who should parameterize procedures, not their creators.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe cybernetic exchange between man, computer and algorithm is like a game of musical chairs: The frantic search for balance always leaves one of the three standing ill at ease.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf your computer speaks English, it was probably made in Japan.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mA year spent in artificial intelligence is enough to make one believe in God.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mProlonged contact with the computer turns mathematicians into clerks and vice versa.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIn computing, turning the obvious into the useful is a living definition of the word \"frustration\".\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWe are on the verge: Today our program proved Fermat's next-to-last theorem.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWhat is the difference between a Turing machine and the modern computer? It's the same as that between Hillary's ascent of Everest and the establishment of a Hilton hotel on its peak.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mMotto for a research laboratory: What we work on today, others will first think of tomorrow.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThough the Chinese should adore APL, it's FORTRAN they put their money on.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWe kid ourselves if we think that the ratio of procedure to data in an active data-base system can be made arbitrarily small or even kept small.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWe have the mini and the micro computer. In what semantic niche would the pico computer fall?\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIt is not the computer's fault that Maxwell's equations are not adequate to design the electric motor.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mOne does not learn computing by using a hand calculator, but one can forget arithmetic.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mComputation has made the tree flower.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe computer reminds one of Lon Chaney -- it is the machine of a thousand faces.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe computer is the ultimate polluter: its feces are indistinguish- able from the food it produces.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWhen someone says \"I want a programming language in which I need only say what I wish done,\" give him a lollipop.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mInterfaces keep things tidy, but don't accelerate growth: Functions do.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mDon't have good ideas if you aren't willing to be responsible for them.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mComputers don't introduce order anywhere as much as they expose opportunities.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWhen a professor insists computer science is X but not Y, have compassion for his graduate students.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIn computing, the mean time to failure keeps getting shorter.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIn man-machine symbiosis, it is man who must adjust: The machines can't.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWe will never run out of things to program as long as there is a single program around.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mDealing with failure is easy: Work hard to improve. Success is also easy to handle: You've solved the wrong problem. Work hard to improve.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mOne can't proceed from the informal to the formal by formal means.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mPurely applicative languages are poorly applicable.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe proof of a system's value is its existence.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mYou can't communicate complexity, only an awareness of it.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIt's difficult to extract sense from strings, but they're the only communication coin we can count on.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe debate rages on: is PL/I Bachtrian or Dromedary?\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWhenever two programmers meet to criticize their programs, both are silent.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThink of it! With VLSI we can pack 100 ENIACS in 1 sq. cm.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mEditing is a rewording activity.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWhy did the Roman Empire collapse? What is Latin for office automation?\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mComputer Science is embarrassed by the computer.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe only constructive theory connecting neuroscience and psychology will arise from the study of software.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mWithin a computer natural language is unnatural.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mMost people find the concept of programming obvious, but the doing impossible.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mYou think you know when you can learn, are more sure when you can write, even more when you can teach, but certain when you can program.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIt goes against the grain of modern education to teach children to program. What fun is there in making plans, acquiring discipline in organizing thoughts, devoting attention to detail and learning to be self-critical?\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIf you can imagine a society in which the computer- robot is the only menial, you can imagine anything.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mProgramming is an unnatural act.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mAdapting old programs to fit new machines usually means adapting new machines to behave like old ones.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan J. Perlis\e[0m"
	"\e[0mBeware of bugs in the above code; I have only proved it correct, not tried it.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mDonald E. Knuth\e[0m"
	"\e[0mScience is knowledge which we understand so well that we can teach it to a computer; and if we don't fully understand something, it is an art to deal with it.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mDonald E. Knuth\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIn fact, my main conclusion after spending ten years of my life working on the TEX project is that software is hard. Its harder than anything else Ive ever had to do.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mDonald E. Knuth\e[0m"
	"\e[0mLet us change our traditional attitude to the construction of programs: Instead of imagining that our main task is to instruct a computer what to do, let us concentrate rather on explaining to human beings what we want a computer to do.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mDonald E. Knuth\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe real problem is that programmers have spent far too much time worrying about efficiency in the wrong places and at the wrong times; premature optimization is the root of all evil (or at least most of it) in programming.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mDonald E. Knuth\e[0m"
	"\e[0mTesting shows the presence, not the absence of bugs.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mEdsger W. Dijkstra\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe competent programmer is fully aware of the strictly limited size of his own skull; therefore he approaches the programming task in full humility, and among other things he avoids clever tricks like the plague.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mEdsger W. Dijkstra\e[0m"
	"\e[0mLISP has been jokingly described as \"the most intelligent way to misuse a computer\". I think that description a great compliment because it transmits the full flavor of liberation: it has assisted a number of our most gifted fellow humans in thinking previously impossible thoughts.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mEdsger W. Dijkstra\e[0m"
	"\e[0mBesides a mathematical inclination, an exceptionally good mastery of one's native tongue is the most vital asset of a competent programmer.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mEdsger W. Dijkstra\e[0m"
	"\e[0mSimplicity is a great virtue but it requires hard work to achieve it and education to appreciate it. And to make matters worse: complexity sells better.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mEdsger W. Dijkstra\e[0m"
	"\e[0mMy point today is that, if we wish to count lines of code, we should not regard them as \"lines produced\" but as \"lines spent\": the current conventional wisdom is so foolish as to book that count on the wrong side of the ledger.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mEdsger W. Dijkstra\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThere are two ways of constructing a software design. One way is to make it so simple that there are obviously no deficiencies. And the other way is to make it so complicated that there are no obvious deficiencies.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mC.A.R. Hoare\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThere are only two hard things in Computer Science: cache invalidation and naming things.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mPhil Karlton\e[0m"
	"\e[0mAlways code as if the guy who ends up maintaining your code will be a violent psychopath who knows where you live.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mMartin Golding\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe trouble with programmers is that you can never tell what a programmer is doing until its too late.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mSeymour Cray\e[0m"
	"\e[0mFirst learn computer science and all the theory. Next develop a programming style. Then forget all that and just hack.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mGeorge Carrette\e[0m"
	"\e[0mDebugging is twice as hard as writing the code in the first place. Therefore, if you write the code as cleverly as possible, you are, by definition, not smart enough to debug it.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mBrian W. Kernighan\e[0m"
	"\e[0mMeasuring programming progress by lines of code is like measuring aircraft building progress by weight.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mBill Gates\e[0m"
	"\e[0mThe best programmers are not marginally better than merely good ones. They are an order-of-magnitude better, measured by whatever standard: conceptual creativity, speed, ingenuity of design, or problem-solving ability.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mRandall E. Stross\e[0m"
	"\e[0mFor a long time it puzzled me how something so expensive, so leading edge, could be so useless. And then it occurred to me that a computer is a stupid machine with the ability to do incredibly smart things, while computer programmers are smart people with the ability to do incredibly stupid things. They are, in short, a perfect match.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mBill Bryson\e[0m"
	"\e[0mYou cant have great software without a great team, and most software teams behave like dysfunctional families.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mJim McCarthy\e[0m"
	"\e[0mIncorrect documentation is often worse than no documentation.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mBertrand Meyer\e[0m"
	"\e[0mCorrectness is clearly the prime quality. If a system does not do what it is supposed to do, then everything else about it matters little.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mBertrand Meyer\e[0m"
	"\e[0mI would love to change the world, but they won't give me the source code.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAnonymous\e[0m"
	"\e[0mAny fool can write code that a computer can understand. Good programmers write code that humans can understand.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mMartin Fowler\e[0m"
	"\e[0mI am not a great programmer; I am just a good programmer with great habits.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mKent Beck\e[0m"
	"\e[0mA Computer is a state machine. Threads are for people who can't program state machines.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mAlan Cox\e[0m"
	"\e[0mNot everything worth doing is worth doing well.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mTom West\e[0m"
	"\e[0mPeace comes from thinking.\n\t\e[1m\e[96mN.S.A\e[0m"
)
